1. Editing Users

Editing users will follow the same pattern as editing anything else. We need a get method, view and a post method.

But first we need some classes that will help us make this easier.

  1. Create Role Class

Go to the models folder and create a new class called Role. A role will have a name and a Boolean value:

  1. Create a View Model

For this task, we need a view model. View models are classes that are used solely for providing information to a view.

In the models folder create a class called EditUserViewModel:

The class will have everything we need to edit a user: the user itself, properties for password and confirm password and a list of roles.

First, add the user:

Next, add the password and confirm password:

Notice that through the attributes we make sure that the two will be the same.

And lastly, add the list of roles:

  1. Creating the Get Method

Inside the Get method we need to instantiate the view model and fill it with information. Let's think of that for a moment:

We need to check if the id is valid and then create the view model and pass it to the view. Let’s do that:

  1. Validate the Id

  1. Get the user from the database

Notice that in step 4, we are using a method to get the user roles. Unfortunately, we can't do it so easily, so we need a separate method for it.

  1. Get User Roles Method

In order to get the all user roles, we are going to need both the role manager and the user manager. Also, we are going to collect all of the roles in a List<Role> and return it as a result.

Let’s view the pseudo code for the method:

We are going to get all roles, no matter if the user is in it or not. For each role, we will mark if the user is in it (That is why we needed the property of the class Role, IsSelected). That way we can tell the view which role will be checked initially.

  1. Create the managers. You are familiar with them already:

  1. Create a list with the names of all roles

  1. Create a Role object for each role and mark if the user is in it

  1. Return the List<Role>

  1. Creating the View

Creating the view is straightforward. Create it inside "Views/User" and name it "Edit". Copy and paste the following code:

@model Blog.Models.EditUserViewModel


@{

ViewBag.Title = "Edit";

}


<div class="container">

<div class="well">

<h2>Edit User</h2>

@Html.ValidationSummary()

@Html.AntiForgeryToken()


@using (Html.BeginForm("Edit", "User", FormMethod.Post, new { @class = "form-horizontal" }))

{

<div class="form-group">

@Html.LabelFor(m => m.User.Email, new { @class = "control-label col-sm-4" })

<div class="col-sm-4">

@Html.TextBoxFor(m => m.User.Email, new { @class = "form-control" })

</div>

</div>


<div class="form-group">

@Html.LabelFor(m => m.User.FullName, new { @class = "control-label col-sm-4" })

<div class="col-sm-4">

@Html.TextBoxFor(m => m.User.FullName, new { @class = "form-control" })

</div>

</div>


<div class="form-group">

@Html.LabelFor(m => m.Password, new { @class = "control-label col-sm-4" })

<div class="col-sm-4">

@Html.TextBoxFor(m => m.Password, new { @class = "form-control" })

</div>

</div>


<div class="form-group">

@Html.LabelFor(m => m.ConfirmPassword, new { @class = "control-label col-sm-4" })

<div class="col-sm-4">

@Html.TextBoxFor(m => m.ConfirmPassword, new { @class = "form-control" })

</div>

</div>


<div class="form-group">

@for (int i = 0; i < Model.Roles.Count; i++)

{

<div class="col-sm-offset-4 col-sm-4">

@Html.HiddenFor(m => m.Roles[i].Name)

@Html.CheckBoxFor(m => m.Roles[i].IsSelected)

@Model.Roles[i].Name

</div>

}

</div>


<div class="form-group">

<div class="col-sm-4 col-sm-offset-4">

<input type="submit" value="Edit" class="btn btn-success" />

</div>

</div>

}

</div>

</div>


The only thing that needs attention is how we are visualizing the checkboxes for each role. This is happening in a loop in which we use a helper method @Html.CheckBoxFor(). Also, we have a hidden field, that helps to bind the information to the view model, because we need it in the post method.

You can now test if the edit button and the view are working properly:

  1. Save changes to the database



There is one more helper method, that we need to take care of - the one for setting the user roles.

  1. Set User Roles Method

For setting user roles, use this method:

It's a helper method that loops through all roles that we received from the form in the view. For each role, it checks weather it is selected. Based on that, the user either receives a new role or is removed from it.
